REGULAR EXPRESSIONS (REGEX)

used to:
- Determine if a string matches a given template (email, address, URL)
- All the substrings of the string matches a given template.

A special template marker to identify character types:
.		Dot, any character
\d		A digit: [0-9]
\D		A non-digit: [^0-9]
\s 		A whitespace character: [\t\n\xOB\f\r]
\S 		A non-whitespace character: [^'s]
\w		A word character: [a-zA-Z_0-9]

Quantifiers can be used to specify the number or length that part of a pattern should match or repeat
*		Match 0 or more times
+ 		Match 1 ore more times
? 		Match 1 or 0 times
{n}		Match exactly n times
{n,}	Match at least n times
{n,m}	Match at least n but not more than m times

 Meta-characters are used to group, divide, and perform special operations in patterns.
 \		Escape the next meta-character (it becomes a normal/literal character)
 ^ 		Match the beginning of the line
 .		Match any character (except newline)
 $ 		Match the end of the line (or before newline at the end)
 |		Alternation ('or' statement)
 ()		Grouping
 []		Custom character class
 
 Visual regex tester: http://regexpal.com/